<TITLE> Internet bandwidth fees slashed for operators </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 16 (bdnews24.com)Bangladesh Telecommunication Regulatory Commission announced Thursday the cost of internet bandwidth for operators will to be reduced by 33 percent, in a move designed to stimulate the telecommunications sector throughout the country. The BTRC statement said public and private internet service providers will now pay Tk 18,000 per megabit/second to the state-run Bangladesh Submarine Cable Company Limited (BSCCL), rather than the current rate of Tk 27,000. Bangladesh Telecommunications Company (BTCL) reduced the price of internal backhaul  from the landing station to Dhaka  while the BSCCL also agreed to reduce their fees, said the statement. BTRC said the mobile phone companies and internet service providers have agreed to provide quality services at a reduced a rate from now on. The BTCL said the decision was made in consultation with the ministry of telecommunications and private and public run service providers. BTRC chairman Zia Ahmed said the move would increase the number of internet users and improve internet speeds. Bangladesh is connected with the SE-ME-W-4 submarine cable consortium. The allotted bandwidth is 24 gigabits, although current usage remains at around 8 gigabits. bd
